Just looked at "a second chance", and I guess I'll give my thoughts on it.

It's very flat, and that flatness seems to come from a lack of descriptive flare. For instance, most of the sentences are very simple and they don't vary much. There were constant paragraphs of "Daniel opened the door. Daniel went inside. He sat down and looked around. Daniel saw the waiter approach."

There is little to no description of any scenes, and actions aren't really described with having any thought or reason behind them.

As far as characterization goes, it's a bit one sided. I know that Daniel is 'some fucking guy who lost his job and apartment', and that's literally it. I can see that he is supposed to be portrayed as a victim of a horrible circumstance, but the way you've set it up makes it seem like he's a shitboot who we haven't gotten to know yet. I mean, if someone gets fired because every single person they worked with thought they were a faggot, and the boss dismisses them without warning, and with prejudice, I'm going to assume they're a cunt and deserved it.

Abby seems to be terminally trusting as she instantly offers Daniel a spare bedroom, and she also seems rather aggressively motherly. The character dynamic seems to be "helpless loser who can't do anything for himself" and "mother figure who coddles him", which is kinda gross imo, but if that's what you like, you do you.

Now, it's established that they knew each other from a while ago, but the nature of how they interacted isn't really established. Daniel doesn't comment on it in any capacity, nor does Abby. No shared memories, or him recalling how she acted back then and comparing it to the present, it's all just sort of glossed over so I have no idea why Abby would be so trusting.

The dialogue is very shallow as well, akin to the sort of conversation you'd have with a cashier while checking out.
